On 2/7/07, Benjamin Carlyle &lt;benjamincarlyle@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; I&#39;m starting to like this approach. Let me have a go at rephrasing it as
&gt; a concrete proposal:
&gt;
&gt; Problem statement: (same as before)
&gt; I have some state that I want to append to a resource. The right method
&gt; according to HTTP is POST, but if I don&#39;t get a response to my POST I
&gt; don&#39;t know whether or not to retry.

I&#39;m not sure what you mean by &quot;append&quot;, but this approach is useful
for both POST(a) as well as POST(p).

&gt;
&gt; Client algorithm:
&gt; ...
&gt; guid = generateGloballyUniqueID();

That would be more of a message id, which is ok if you just want
verifiable once-and-only-once.  But you also have the option of making
the tag value a function of the request representation, which would be
useful in cases where the same representation might be sent in
multiple messages.

Your analysis looks pretty good.

Mark.
